The cells job is failing to boot from volume with a bdm v2 request like:

"block_device_mapping_v2": [{
    "destination_type": "volume",
    "boot_index": 0,
    "uuid": "553083ac-40f2-4225-ac4d-a1d021eb7fb1",
    "source_type": "volume",
    "delete_on_termination": true
}]

Given it seems there should only be one BDM in the list and it's boot
index is 0, we shouldn't fail on the boot sequence validation, so add
some debug logging when we hit that failure.

Also copy some wording out of the 'Block Device Mapping in Nova' section
of the devref to add as code comments for the validation happening so we
have context.

TODO(mriedem): track down ndipanov to figure out why _subsequent_list
omits the last element of the list that it's processing, we need to doc
that logic in the code for maintainability.

Change-Id: I8adc94f3c93c149689fbef424665fb44ac573819
Related-Bug: #1489581

commit_message:
Add debug logging for when boot sequence is invalid in _validate_bdm

The cells job is failing to boot from volume with a bdm v2 request like:

"block_device_mapping_v2": [{
    "destination_type": "volume",
    "boot_index": 0,
    "uuid": "553083ac-40f2-4225-ac4d-a1d021eb7fb1",
    "source_type": "volume",
    "delete_on_termination": true
}]

Given it seems there should only be one BDM in the list and it's boot
index is 0, we shouldn't fail on the boot sequence validation, so add
some debug logging when we hit that failure.

Also copy some wording out of the 'Block Device Mapping in Nova' section
of the devref to add as code comments for the validation happening so we
have context.

TODO(mriedem): track down ndipanov to figure out why _subsequent_list
omits the last element of the list that it's processing, we need to doc
that logic in the code for maintainability.

Change-Id: I8adc94f3c93c149689fbef424665fb44ac573819
Related-Bug: #1489581

commit_message:
Added natural sort for interfaces in utils.ordered_active_nics()

This way device eth10 is after eth9, and not directly after eth1

Change-Id: I81eba97cccf6c4f314f9037d16ee1f244dbade02
Closes-Bug: #1482818

commit_message:
Added postcommit hooks in ovsvapp mech_driver

This patch-set added the postcommit methods for network and port
in ovsvapp mechanism driver which is required by ovsvapp driver.py
sitting in openstack/networking-vsphere repo.

This issue was addressed in 'master' (Mitaka) as part of review:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240127/

Backporting the relevant part of that fix here, since 
cherrypicking is not possible.

Closes-Bug: #1512328

[{'created': '2015-11-03 19:41:12.000000000', 'message': "Switch -xf to xf for tar command

The last commit for this bug caused a bunch of log output since tar doesn't
like having a dash in front of its short options. This patch adjusts the
order of the parameters for tar and removes the dash in front of 'xf'.

This should greatly reduce logging output.

Closes-bug: 1512736

Change-Id: Icf9392c749e3f9731e5bc182a242a2bc11e440a9

commit_message:
Remove dashes from short tar params

Using dashes with tar's short parameters creates a bunch of extra logging
output and warnings.  This should greatly reduce logging output.

Change-Id: Icf9392c749e3f9731e5bc182a242a2bc11e440a9

Fix up magnum-ui setup

Magnum-ui is setup similar to horizon with two django pot files. Invoke
run_tests.sh here.

Change-Id: I09350bfd384f84d132dc03d9bae2a5015acb6b0f

commit_message:
DRAC BIOS vendor_passthru: enable rebooting the node

Changing the BIOS settings require rebooting the node. If the node was
originally powered off, the driver would need to turn it on, poll the
job status on the DRAC card and power off the node. To keep things
simple, the BIOS mgmt vendor_passthru methods avoided doing that.

However, it would be beneficial for the user to let them decide whether
they want to reboot the node automatically after the config job
succeeds. DRAC cards already support this, so the driver doesn't need to
supervise the config job status. With this patch the DRAC vendor
passthru for commit_bios_config accepts a 'reboot' parameter.

Closes-bug: #1508459
Change-Id: Id9a87f6dec6a8d6160948e39a763134729cead99

Temporary disable security for Oozie in Ambari plugin.
That can be returned again when Sahara Oozie client will
be able to authenticate.

Besides the minor nits in the code, I am a little bit concerned whether we should enforce name uniqueness globally. Maybe we should leave this decision to the cloud operator.

My personal experience is that enforcing name uniqueness is a pain when playing with the command line. I have to copy paste the (node) name every time. Speaking of uniquely identifying an object, we already have UUIDs for all objects. It should be okay, at least from my viewpoint, to allow duplicate names. By the way, we already have logics in place to handle ambiguity.

As an alternative, we can add a configuration option to the senlin.conf file. The engine then decide whether duplicate names are okay based on this setting.

Yet another suggestion. This patch is incomplete. This kind of a patch may leave things unnoticed thus sort of introducing new bugs. If name uniqueness is to be enforced, we should propose that in a single patch if the total number of changed lines is not big. Or we can remind the reviewers that there will be future patches to complete this huge work.'}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-10-13 09:46:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I am also not sure if we need this. Refer to other projects like Nova, instance name is not unique. I can't see the merit if we support this, or the demerit if we don't."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 10:58:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

I think the same as others... Enforcing name uniqueness is not really necessary, and we already have UUIDs to provide this. Too much of a headache to head down this path.'}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-14 02:00:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Understand. By comparison, myself is inclined to add a configure option to allow cloud admin to enforce name uniqueness when they believe it is necessary.

For profile, since it doesn't have owner related properties, like project, user, domain, project_safe indexing is not supported yet. I plan to revise profile's DB model to add those properties before enabling name uniqueness checking for it.

Thanks you guys for review. Will hold the patch."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:33:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Think of this situation, if a user in a specific tenant create a new cluster with name like 'foo', but got a name unique error. But at all his tenants, he can not find a cluster with this name. That would be a little odd."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-15 01:53:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, Ethan, I guess that situation won't happen since name uniqueness error will only be raised when cluster query finds existing cluster. And after deliberation, I think maybe we shouldn't provide configure option for name uniqueness enforcement since that could make the behavior of different deployments of senlin service inconsistent and thus confuse the enduser."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-10-16 07:41:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think the difference between different deployments will confuse end users. The simplest way is just allow name duplication. We are already handling that well (hopefully). When a user is referencing an object using name which is not unique in DB (within a project or not), we raise exceptions: be more specific."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-16 07:53:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add config option for name uniqueness

This patch adds a configure option to allow cloud administrator to
enable/disable the name unique of Senlin objects that belong
to the same project.

Change-Id: I02e7a58ddc447229d3f0e339e226538d35a35874

commit_message:
Fix the neutron-lbaas agent config

This patch should fix the functional gate. The issue is that devstack
switch to stevedore aliases for interface_driver configuration [1],
but lbaas doesn't use aliases. This patch fixed the broken config.
This patch should be considered as a temporary workaround. We need
to investigate why devstack doesn't populate the correct config at
the first place.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/237519/

Closes-Bug: #1512933
Change-Id: I73b9e146ad4cc253e6a04bcadc07f124a7c96df5

commit_message:
Modify from "xsd:string" to "xsd:dict" for "router"

In Extra routes API, the type of "router" object is set "xsd:string".
This commit fixes the type of "router" to "xsd:dict".

Change-Id: Ic8032536166f4c97eabcf79b51e0c24cba916a35
Closes-Bug: #1512664

commit_message:
Storwize family and SVC driver back-end support

Added documentation for configuring the Storwize
family and SVC driver in OpenStack Configuration
Reference manual.

Details related to backend storage node configuration.
(cinder.conf file changes for multiple backend support)

Change-Id: I985a97bc9bab66be7704874184c664f787ecfc7c
Closes-Bug: #1402570

Raise exception when adding an existed attribute while update bay

This patch raises a reasonable ClientSideError exception when adding
an existed attribute while doing update bay.

Besides, several apply_jsonpatch unit test cased added.
Remove all related add_(existed) attr case of api side.

I think git:// is the best default for everyone.  You can override it if it causes issues.  Something in the documentation about proxies & tweaks for them would probably be good'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-09 02:43:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Can you please provide a reason on why 'git://' is the best default for everyone?

This patch is for fixing the case where 'git://' does not work.  To me this is an example of it not being a good default.  Can an example be provided that shows 'git://' working where 'https://' does not?

The problem with 'git://' is that with proxy servers it requires extra configuration to use a SOCKS proxy.  While 'https://' just works if the environment variable 'https_proxy=...' is set."}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2015-02-09 09:10:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I agree with Ian I'd rather have git:// as default

In my experience https with large repository can have timeout issue.

IMO git:// is a much faster implementation and should work for most of our users"}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-09 13:40:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The Android project has some 'huge' repositories and the only protocol they support is 'https'
 https://android-review.googlesource.com/#/admin/projects/device/lge/hammerhead-kernel

I am not seeing much of a speed difference between 'git://' and 'https:/'.  In fact in my simple test 'https:/'' was a few seconds faster on a 25 Mbit/sec connection

- gate-devstack-publish-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/97/153397/3/check/gate-devstack-publish-docs/68cd408//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 29s'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-02-09 22:14:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As you noted in the commit message, we've been back-and-forth on this a few times.  Configuration for proxies is not our default use-case.  What is it about setting GIT_BASE that does not work for you?"}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-09 22:25:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Dean,

Because it doesn't work out of the box for people behind a proxy server.  And then when it fails a person has to spend most likely a lot of time trying to figure out about the configuration variable GIT_BASE.  So this is a known use case where the default breaks for people.

I work in a company with probably over 120,000 employees.  If any of them attempt to install Devstack out of the box, it fails for them.  Which likely gives them a poor user experience.

My confusion is that I have yet to hear any convincing argument on why 'git://' is superior to 'https:'.  If a case could be explained then fine, I would accept it.  Also if an individual person felt that 'git://' was preferable (which I find debatable), they could use the GIT_BASE variable.

On another note 'https://' appears to be less susceptible to a Man-In-The-Middle attack.

Thanks,
John"}, {'account_id': 1981, 'date': '2015-02-09 22:37:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

This does seem like a reasonable change.  It looks like `http' does cause problems for some people (those that use a proxy) while `https' should work for everyone and therefore makes a better default.  As mentioned, any default can be overwritten."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-09 22:57:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

I don't want to bike-shed over 4 lines of code, but there are at least 3 other reviews out there

Id1869e054e8391be117cfe353cd9d5457e86d1f0
Ie7058600266f033af0836bdc4de5a56e823f8c07
If65cb282adc6f5e4c4507b1422885d81de3da4e8

relating to proxy settings and I'm not sure any of them fix the issues.

People have to live behind proxies ... such is life.

The *first* thing we should merge is simply some documentation about how to use the extant codebase when you're behind a proxy.  Something that someone has actually tested and confirmed.

Then, given the documented framework of things that need to be done to run behind a proxy, we can look at how we can make life easier.  I do not want to see us merging ad-hoc changes when we have no big-picture"}, {'account_id': 12403, 'date': '2015-02-24 04:23:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I think this is a bad idea.  It would break a common use case that I use every day.  I live behind a firewall and often have https_proxy set, but also have my devstack pointing at git:// repos that live behind my firewall.  This fix would suddenly and inexplicably break that setup.'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-24 04:43:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Al Miller,

How do you have your devstack pointing at git:// repos that live behind your firewall?

If you did that by setting GIT_BASE then this patch would have zero impact on your setup.

This is only changing the default setting.  If someone changes the default server than this patch has no effect.  As can be seen in the patch itself.'}, {'account_id': 12403, 'date': '2015-02-24 16:59:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

John, after thinking about this overnight, my hesitation isn't so much about whether the default should be git:// vs https:// as it is with changing git behavior based on the presence of a seemingly unrelated environment variable (https_proxy).  This seems unintuitive and I am afraid there will be unintended consequences for someone down the line.

I realize you are trying to find a fix for a frustrating situation (I feel the firewall/proxy pain every day too) but I worry that there will be users for whom this change will cause confusion."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-25 04:56:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Al,

1.  Do you still think this patch breaks your use case, as you mentioned before?

2.  Do you have any ideas of a use case that you think will break because of this.  You mention unintended consequences, which is of course true.  But that could be said of almost all patches.  So I'm hoping to get an idea of possible concrete examples.  I don't want this blocked because it is possible that we might break someone but we have no idea how.

3.  It sounds like you are more in favor of just moving to https as always the default.  Is that true?  That was my first patch but I got push-back on it.  So why I did this to only do it for people who are behind a proxy server.  As it is right now devstack is broken out-of-the-box for people behind a proxy server.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-02-25 07:45:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

it's a little surprising that https_proxy env affects git vs https."}, {'account_id': 12487, 'date': '2015-02-25 08:33:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I really don't think making "https" as default breaks things.
Here the intention is to make devstack workable for everyone than enhancing the performance.'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-27 18:49:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 12403, 'date': '2015-03-16 18:26:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

John, sorry to not get back to this sooner.  Yes, I do think this would break a use case that I have, which is:

1) I have a local dev machine that contains the repos that I use to build my devstack, and to which I commit my changes (in neutron-lbaas).  I've got the git daemon running on that box.

2) From my test machine, I have https_proxy set so I can browse the web and retrieve external git repos via https.

3) When I run stack.sh, it points to my personal git repo server, but web browsing, apt-get, etc use the corporate proxy.

4) In this case, if devstack decided for me that I really wanted https for git, the git requests would time out,  since I'm not running an http server on my dev box."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-03-16 20:32:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Al,

Happy to discuss this on IRC.  I am jlvillal.

I don't believe that this patch breaks your use case as you said:

3) When I run stack.sh, it points to my personal git repo server, but web browsing, apt-get, etc use the corporate proxy.

I'm assuming this means that you have set GIT_BASE.

This patch does nothing if GIT_BASE has been set by the user.  If you review the patch you can see how it works.

If you have not set GIT_BASE then I'm curious how you have done step 3 to have it point at personal git repo."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-11-04 04:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Use 'https' protocol if 'https_proxy' environment var is set

If the user has set the 'https_proxy' environment variable then assume
they are behind a proxy server.  In that case use 'https://' as the git
protocol.  Otherwise keep using the 'git://' protocol.  The user can
still override the value by setting the variable GIT_BASE

The 'https://' protocol is easily handled by proxy servers.  The
'git://' protocol requires a rather complex configuration to use through
a proxy server.

Using 'git://' as the protocol requires more extensive configuration of
proxy servers and in particular requires usage of a SOCKS proxy.  While
'https://' is easily handled by setting the environment variable
'https_proxy'.

Change-Id: Ib59c5b5cc986dacea2c31a787c89040e7534010e
Signed-off-by: John L. Villalovos <john.l.villalovos@intel.com>

Capitalize a Few Words

There are a few words that I have noticed throughout Keystone
that should be capitalized when they were not.  The few words
I fix are: Fernet, SQLite and MySQL.

This patch is mainly porting from nova repository:

Adds:
1.tools/flake8wrap.sh
  Will let developer use 'tox -epep8 -- -HEAD' to testing changes files
2.tools/pretty_tox.sh
  Give pretty test trace when doing unit/functional testing.

Change-Id: Icedb4ed8b50532531e18784a1584fe63c5a9e017

commit_message:
Improve tox.ini to easy developer's life

This patch is mainly porting from nova repository:

Adds:
1.tools/flake8wrap.sh
  Will let developer use 'tox -epep8 -- -HEAD' to testing changes files
2.tools/pretty_tox.sh
  Give pretty test trace when doing unit/functional testing.

Change-Id: Icedb4ed8b50532531e18784a1584fe63c5a9e017

commit_message:
Adapt resource path to server revision

This patch revises the resource path names where underscores are used.
With recent patch at server side, the client needs to talk to the server
using the revised resource path.

Change-Id: Ia7d2f5b2b7b310e37e601e60b70f04c366fd3009
ref: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240740/

Just for clarity, as mentioned on the opposing review, the reason this is wrong is because response codes refer to the resource identified by the URI in the request.

This proposal violates that rule.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 11:51:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

404 is wrong, but all other are so much worse, so I vote for this one.'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:16:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

i tend to agree with Chris, but i hate to just see us swap +1s/-1s on these reviews lol.'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-10-09 21:07:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

For all the semantic reasons that 400 is not right, those same arguments apply here. 

Not Found is not an appropriate response to a modification of an existing resource or the creation of a legitimate resource under the correct endpoint.

This would be contrary to common expectation of web users and API consumers because Not Found is such a specific and well understood error.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-13 08:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Common sense from the 404 words would fit to this situation, but it is difficult to make this as a guideline from a common sense because  this is against the rule..'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-10-22 22:26:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The alternative is merged, so unnecessary now.'}]

commit_message:
Networking Guide - Provider Network image misleading

Changed "provider network" to "tenant network" and
"provider network" is identified between the neutron router and
the physical infrastructure.

Change-Id: Ide7d131d95eea96af8c87f425e566c7eb6357d7a
Closes-Bug: #1511799

commit_message:
Add useful links to project README.rst

Add more information in README.rst

Include
* showing the latest package version and download count on top
* list source links relative to manila like PyPi, Launchpad project,
Blueprints, Bugs, Source, and How to Contribute.

Frozen. To be merged on Oct. 16 if there's no further feedback."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-10-08 22:05:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7634, 'date': '2015-10-09 06:23:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 08:15:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

What was the reasoning behind this? 400 is a wrong code for non-existing things, wherever they appear. This change would make life for people (if some would try to adopt this, which I doubt) substantially harder: instead of raising FlavorNotFound (I'm roughly following the example in the guideline) and taking code 404 from it, API level must catch all exceptions and replace 404 codes for 400 based on some logic."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-09 08:53:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

API guideline should be based on http spec, not current implementation of each project.

Lower layer methods would return NotFound exceptions as you said, but it is good to consider to translate these exceptions to accurate error status code if the http spec covers these cases as an ideal guideline.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 08:55:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

> to accurate error status code

400 for not found is an accurate status code?'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:07:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Also re:

> API guideline should be based on http spec, not current implementation of each project.

The whole reason we even have API guidelines instead of just following the RFC, is that the HTTP protocol was designed for hypertext, not for making API's. In particular, it terribly lacks proper status code (e.g. we have big problems in ironic with our "node locked" error). So yes, we have to think about existing implementations . All projects I worked on used code 404 in this case.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:09:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Did you see rfc2616 which is mentioned in this patch?
This patch includes the reason to avoid usage of 404.

and if we cannot use 404, I cannot find the other code except 400 from the following list.

 400 Bad Request
 401 Unauthorized
 402 Payment Required
 403 Forbidden
 404 Not Found
 405 Method Not Allowed
 406 Not Acceptable
 407 Proxy Authentication Required
 408 Request Timeout
 409 Conflict
 410 Gone
 411 Length Required
 412 Precondition Failed
 413 Request Entity Too Large
 414 Request-URI Too Long
 415 Unsupported Media Type
 416 Requested Range Not Satisfiable
 417 Expectation Failed'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:15:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

> and if we cannot use 404, I cannot find the other code except 400 from the following list.

that's why we have to uses 404. we don't have code stating "subresource not found". and that's why ironic has to use 409 for node locked, though it's a huge pain in the neck for everyone. HTTP was not initially designed for API, so let's apply common sense :)'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:16:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/232972/ is alternative proposal against this.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:18:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

> so let's apply common sense :)

It's also nice point, thanks ;)

Maybe alternative proposal also will be a nice option for this. I just want to know opinions now."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:27:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I'm not convinced that 400 is the right return code for it, the same RFC says that 400 should be raised due syntax problems and the situation described in the guide is a logical problem."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:30:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Dmitry I think the issue here is that 404 needs to be used only in the specific instance of the resource named in the URI not being there.

The 400, in this guideline, is for stating that the resource named in the URI is attempting to reference, in its representation, something that is not there and thus the _representation_ is invalid. The resource itself does exist but the state being represented is not okay.

I agree that it is disorienting but for the effective use of APIs it is critical that we use response codes to talk about the resource in the URI.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-10-09 09:33:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 11:57:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

>  something that is not there and thus the _representation_ is invalid

I disagree with this interpretation of both the situation and the 400 code. As a developer using API I want distinguishable error codes more than trying to follow every letter of an RFC's designed for hypertext.. We already make this mistake with HTTP 409 in ironic, I don't want to repeat it.

Also, if we go down this path, we need to consider:

1. What if a subresource is inaccessible by a user (aka 403)? My logic tells me to return 403 for the whole action (as it's unauthorized), logic in this guideline demands 400.

2. What if a subresource is temporary unavailable (aka 503)? Following the same logic one could argue that we need 400 here as well.."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:12:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

Here is a real issue where this exposed.

Nova used to return a 404 on the following kind of request:

DELETE /v2/floating-ips/172.100.100.100

Here's the thing, the url for a floating ip isn't that. It's /v2/floating-ips/$id.

The shade library implemented code around floating ips to clean them up, and the DELETE code hit a 404, which meant is assumed that all was good and the thing was gone. Which is wrong. It meant it called a completely unpossible url. A 404 is expected by the user for a resource that could exist, but does not.

We changed this to a 400 when applying strict validation. This blew up the shade code. We all looked at it and both they as a user, and us as a producer, were much happier with the new behavior. It meant they got to know they were building requests incorrectly, not just that the thing they were looking for didn't exist."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:21:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Sean, I may be completely unaware of details, but 400 sounds just as wrong as 404. I would make it not fail, otherwise you ended up with a non-deletable resource just due to the fact that part of it is already deleted :) Again, I'm sorry if the issue is just more complex than I just imagined.

Having said that, I more and more think that there could not be a good guideline covering all cases, and that "apply common sense" is the best thing to do here.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:25:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Ok, seems like I've misread it, but after a second glance it still does not look correct to me. So for all non-existing API you return error 400, right? I.e. if I call /v2/foobar on Nova, I'll get 400? Or is it only for malformed ID's?"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:40:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I think there's some confusion between the case that Sean has presented and the guideline that is actually being proposed. The guideline says:

"resource in the body (not url)"

In that specific case 400 makes sense.

Sean's example (where there is a malformed id in the URL) does not make sense as a 400 (to me). That should be a 404 as that is what HTTP requires and seriously, let's try to use it.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:57:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

>Sean's example (where there is a malformed id in the URL) >does not make sense as a 400 (to me). That should be a 404 >as that is what HTTP requires and seriously, let's try to >use it.

+1

...

But my main concern with this patch is the HTTP 400 being returned if a non-existent ID is found in the body message. I get that the section for the HTTP 404 says "The server has not found anything  matching the Request-URI" and I'm OK having another return code for that situation (even tho I personally would prefer 404), but, HTTP 400 is not the right code, the same RFC says:

10.4.1 400 Bad Request

   The request could not be understood by the server due to malformed syntax. The client SHOULD NOT repeat the request without modifications.

A non-existent ID in the body message *is not* a syntax error. We can't just cherry-pick parts of the RFC that we like and ignore others, IMHO.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:00:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

> The client SHOULD NOT repeat the request without modifications.

This part also does not apply in this case: exactly the same request might succeed in 2 seconds, if e.g. an async creation of a resource finishes.'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:10:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

good points raised by Lucas and Dmitry. for me this breaks down into how do we distinguish between an unfound, or non-existant, URI and something that is wrong with the body.

i think the idea behind using the 400 in these cases is to help resolve where is the error is being generated. perhaps this is too strict a reading of the RFC, but the idea of "404==bad uri" and "400==bad body" seem to make sense to me.

just my $0.02'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:11:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

also, i agree with Lucas that a an unfound resource is not exactly a "syntax error" in the body.'}, {'account_id': 177, 'date': '2015-10-09 18:35:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I vote 422 I think, but using 404 for this has definitely been confusing for me in the past.'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-10-09 20:56:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

I am convinced at this point that this should be a 422 instead.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-10-09 21:15:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

-1 for referencing the outdated and no longer accurate 2616 spec. HTTP 1.1 is now defined in RFCs 7230, 7231, 7233, 7234, and 7235'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-10-13 00:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Ian, thanks for your point.
That is a nice input for me, I will update this based on 7231.

re: 422 vs 400

The same question is here: 
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/16133923/400-vs-422-response-to-post-of-data

As the above question, on the latest rfc(7231), malformed request syntax is one of examples of 400. and now I prefer using 400 for this situation.

commit_message:
Add http400 for reference to nonexistent resource

We tend to use "404 NotFound" for all nonexistent resource cases
due to the name, but the RFC says its usage and we need to use 400
for some cases. This patch adds these cases for avoiding confusions.

Change-Id: Ie6e461a133a62de1c87b4b6d963c02fa91aca63c
